# Customer Churn Prediction (ML Classification Project)

Predicts whether a telecom customer will churn (leave the service) based on
their account details, usage, and support history. Intermediate-level project
covering the full ML pipeline: data generation → EDA → preprocessing →
model training/comparison → evaluation → inference.

## Why a synthetic dataset?

This project generates a **synthetic but realistic** dataset (`data_generator.py`)
that mirrors the well-known Telco Customer Churn dataset in structure and
feature relationships (contract type, tenure, monthly charges, support calls,
etc.), with churn probability driven by real business logic plus noise —
not random labels. It also injects missing values so `preprocessing.py` has
genuine cleaning work to do. Swap in a real CSV with the same columns any
time by replacing `data/customer_churn.csv`.

## Project structure

```
churn_project/
├── requirements.txt      # dependencies
├── utils.py               # shared paths, column config, helpers
├── data_generator.py      # step 1: creates data/customer_churn.csv
├── eda.py                 # step 2: exploratory analysis + charts
├── preprocessing.py       # step 3: cleaning, encoding, split, scaling
├── train_model.py         # step 4: trains & compares 3 models
├── evaluate.py             # step 5: test-set metrics + charts
├── predict.py              # step 6: inference on new customers
├── data/                   # generated CSVs (created on run)
├── models/                 # saved model + encoders + scaler (created on run)
└── outputs/                # saved PNG charts (created on run)
```

## Setup

```bash
pip install -r requirements.txt
```

## How to run (in order)

```bash
python data_generator.py   # 1. create the dataset
python eda.py               # 2. explore it, save charts to outputs/
python preprocessing.py     # 3. clean + encode + split + scale
python train_model.py       # 4. train Logistic Regression / Random Forest / Gradient Boosting, keep the best
python evaluate.py          # 5. evaluate the best model on the test set
python predict.py           # 6. run a demo prediction on two sample customers
```

## Models compared

| Model               | 5-fold CV ROC-AUC |
|---------------------|-------------------|
| Logistic Regression | ~0.71              |
| Random Forest        | ~0.72 (best)        |
| Gradient Boosting     | ~0.72               |

`class_weight="balanced"` is used on Logistic Regression and Random Forest so
the model doesn't just ignore churners to chase raw accuracy — recall on the
churn class matters more than overall accuracy in a real retention use case.

## Using `predict.py` in your own code

```python
from predict import predict_churn

result = predict_churn({
    "gender": "Female", "senior_citizen": 0, "partner": "Yes",
    "dependents": "No", "tenure_months": 3, "contract_type": "Month-to-month",
    "internet_service": "Fiber optic", "tech_support": "No",
    "payment_method": "Electronic check", "monthly_charges": 89.5,
    "total_charges": 268.5, "num_support_calls": 4,
})
print(result)  # {'churn_prediction': 'Yes', 'churn_probability': 0.87}
```

## Possible extensions

- Hyperparameter tuning with `GridSearchCV` / `RandomizedSearchCV`
- SHAP values for per-customer explainability
- Wrap `predict_churn` in a small Flask/FastAPI service
- Try SMOTE for oversampling instead of `class_weight`
